      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":334,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a fully conversational effort. You should be able to speak in full sentences throughout. This is aerobic base-building — resist the urge to push.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 5 minutes of brisk walking and dynamic leg swings before easing into your easy pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of easy walking and light calf and hip flexor stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This easy run anchors your aerobic base for the week. At VDOT 49.7, your easy zone (5:04–5:34/km) is where the majority of your aerobic adaptations happen — mitochondrial density, fat oxidation, and cardiac efficiency. There's no such thing as 'too slow' here. If anything, erring toward the slower end (5:30–5:34/km) on this day preserves energy for your quality sessions later in the week.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":252,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational jog. Use this time to settle your breathing and loosen your legs before the work begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First threshold cruise interval at 4:12/km. Comfortably hard — you can speak a few words but not hold a conversation. Controlled and smooth.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery between cruise intervals. Keep moving — don't stop.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second threshold cruise interval. Maintain the same controlled effort as the first. Focus on relaxed shoulders and steady breathing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third and final cruise interval. If you're feeling strong, this one should feel the same as the first — not harder. That's the goal.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog cooldown. Let your heart rate come down gradually before stopping.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jog at 5:30–5:34/km before the first interval. Include 4–6 strides in the final 2 minutes of warmup to prime your legs.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jog at 5:30/km. Follow with hamstring, quad, and calf stretches held for 30 seconds each.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals at threshold pace (4:12/km) are one of the most powerful tools for marathon preparation. They raise your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain before lactate accumulates faster than you can clear it. For a 3:15 marathon (4:37/km goal), a strong threshold is the physiological foundation. Three 8-minute reps with 2-minute jog recoveries gives you 24 minutes of quality threshold work — right in the sweet spot for this phase of training. The short recoveries keep lactate elevated and make this more specific than a single continuous tempo run.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":334,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This run is purely about active recovery and keeping your legs moving before Sunday's long run. Run by feel — if 5:34/km feels right, use it. There is no pace floor here.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of walking before easing into your easy jog.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes of walking. Focus on hip flexor and glute stretches to prepare for Sunday.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday's easy run serves two purposes: it keeps your weekly volume on track and primes your legs with light movement the day before your long run. Research supports that a short, easy run the day before a long run can actually improve glycogen storage and neuromuscular readiness compared to complete rest. Keep this genuinely easy — 5:30–5:34/km is ideal. If your legs feel heavy from Thursday's threshold work, slow down further or shorten to 6 km. Listen to your body.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":26,\"target_duration_minutes\":140,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":344,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very easy — even slower than your normal easy pace. The first 10 minutes are just waking your body up. No ego here.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":95,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady aerobic running at 5:04–5:34/km. Stay conversational. This is the bulk of the long run — building time on feet, fat oxidation, and muscular endurance. Fuel every 45 minutes with your race-day nutrition strategy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 4–5 km at marathon pace (4:28/km). This is the key stimulus of this long run — teaching your body to run at goal pace on tired legs. This is race-specific adaptation. Focus on form: tall posture, relaxed arms, quick cadence.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":344,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog back to easy pace for the final 2–3 km. Let your heart rate come down before stopping completely.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at a very easy walk-jog for the first 5 minutes. No need for formal warmup drills — the first 2 km of the run itself serves as the warmup.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After finishing, walk for 5–10 minutes. Prioritize hydration and a carbohydrate-protein snack within 30 minutes. Spend 10 minutes on static stretching — calves, hamstrings, hip flexors, and glutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is the cornerstone workout of your week and your marathon preparation. At 26 km, you're already running a strong long run distance — your recent training history shows you're comfortable here. The structure — easy aerobic running followed by a marathon-pace finish — is one of the most evidence-based marathon workouts available. It trains fat oxidation at easy pace, then switches metabolic gears to marathon-specific intensity on fatigued legs, which is exactly what race day demands. The 4:28/km marathon pace finish (approximately 4–5 km) is challenging but achievable given your 1:32 half marathon fitness. Use this run to practice your race-day fueling strategy — gels, chews, or whatever you plan to use on September 5th. Never try anything new on race day.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
